<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-21T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-21T13:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 867n.01/2</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-21T18:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 22, 2.05
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>8033. Your 6041, December 15, 3 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d407fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_473">p.
                                    473</ref>.</note>
                                <persName corresp="#p_CLR1">Lord Robert Cecil</persName>, in charge
                                of Foreign Office while Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BAJ1">Balfour</persName> is ill, informed us that the British
                                Government has an understanding with the French Government that
                                Palestine shall be internationalized. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BAJ1">Balfour</persName>’s letter, printed in the
                                    <hi rend="italic">Times</hi> of November 9, merely [stated] that
                                the British Government pledges itself to put [apparent omission] the
                                Jews in Palestine on the same footing as other nationalities. No
                                discrimination shall be made against them. This is as far as the
                                British Government has yet gone.</p>
                            <p>Then followed an informal conversation. An internationalized
                                Palestine must be under the protection of some great power.
                                    <persName corresp="#p_CLR1">Lord Robert</persName> speaking only
                                for himself feared that the continental powers would not agree that
                                any one of them should hold the protectorate and some of them would
                                object even to England’s holding it. Still speaking informally and
                                only for himself he hoped that the United States would consent to be
                                the protecting power when the time comes, and he felt sure that all
                                the powers would gladly agree.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>